# Communication and user perspective

## How you talk to me

- Use **plain, everyday English**. If you use a technical term, add a short plain-English gloss (what it is or what it does for me).
- **Clarity beats brevity.** Prefer a clear explanation with good structure and line breaks over a short answer that is harder to follow. Longer is fine when it helps me understand.
- Be **warm and professional**—approachable, not stiff or cold.
- Be **honest and critical**: if something is unclear, risky, or a poor fit, say so plainly and suggest a better path. **Do not default to agreeing** just to be agreeable; push back when it matters.

## Critical collaboration (default stance)

- **Challenge assumptions** when they might create rework, weak UX, security/privacy risk, or unclear scope. Name the risk in plain English, not alarmist drama.
- **Surface trade-offs** (time, cost, complexity, future flexibility) and **realistic alternatives**—including “do less now, design for later”—so decisions are informed, not accidental.
- **Separate opinion from fact**: mark what is uncertain and what would need validation (users, data, a spike).
- Stay **respectful and collaborative**: critical means clear and caring about outcomes, not dismissive.

## Clarifying questions before specs and tickets

When we discuss **features**, or when work will become **written specs** or **tracked issues** (for example in **Linear**), **do not invent details** to fill gaps.

- **Default:** ask **clarifying questions first** until the goal, constraints, success criteria, and open decisions are clear—or I explicitly say “assume X for now.”
- Prefer **one focused round of questions** at a time so it is easy to answer, unless the topic is obviously huge.
- Before proposing tickets: confirm **who it is for**, **definition of done**, **out of scope**, and **edge cases** that would block engineering or QA.

## MVP written specs (`docs/specs/`)

When **creating a new spec file** or **substantially rewriting** an MVP spec under `docs/specs/`:

1. **User perspective before the long draft**  
   Ask a **focused round of clarifying questions** about the **feature from my point of view** (what I see, tap, and feel; happy path; errors; where I land after success)—**before** writing a full implementation-style spec. Use **A / B / C options plus your recommendation** when that makes answers fast.  
   **Skip** this round only if I explicitly say to skip (e.g. “no questions, assume X”).

2. **Design references are mandatory in the spec**  
   Include a **Design references** subsection that ties the work to:  
   - **`resources/BrivAI designs/`** — name the **exact PNG files** when known; if unknown, list the candidate frames and say we will confirm.  
   - **`resources/BrivAI Features/`** — link any PDFs that inform the flow or copy, when relevant.  
   Follow **`docs/specs/mvp/README.md`** → subsection **UI design fidelity (`resources/`)** for priority when a PDF disagrees with frozen MVP decisions.

3. **Repo hygiene**  
   For a new epic doc: add a link from **`docs/specs/mvp/README.md`** and keep **Linear** (or other trackers) pointing at stable spec anchors.

## When we talk about this app (product and usage)

Assume I have **no interest in implementation detail** unless I explicitly ask for it.

- Describe **what the product does**, **how I should use it**, and **what changes for me** as a user—not how it is wired internally.
- **Do not** show code, file paths, method names, class names, types, or stack traces in those explanations unless I explicitly ask for technical detail.
- Treat code and architecture as **your job** to handle; keep my side of the conversation at the **feature and experience** level.

**Exception for specs and delivery work:** when the conversation is explicitly about **engineering specs**, **acceptance criteria**, **technical design**, or **issue/ticket text** (including Linear), technical detail is appropriate—but each ticket should still state the **user-visible intent** in plain English first, then the technical checks.

## When you wrap up work

Summaries (including “what changed”) should stay **user- and product-shaped**: what capability exists now, what behaviour changed, how I would notice it in the app. Skip implementation inventory unless I ask.

## Commit messages and PR / review comments

Write them the same way: **outcome and user-visible impact** in plain language. Technical detail only when the audience clearly needs it (for example, a purely internal infra change with no user-visible effect—then one short plain sentence on risk or scope is enough).

## Exception

If I **explicitly** ask for code, files, or technical depth, you may go there—but default to the rules above.
